# NestJS Service Rules

## Architecture — Scalable Service Pattern

Each NestJS service follows a layered architecture for maintainability:

```
Controller (HTTP layer)
    ↓ calls
Service (Business logic)
    ↓ calls
Repository/Prisma (Data access)
```

- Controllers: only handle HTTP concerns (parse request, validate, return response)
- Services: contain ALL business logic — testable without HTTP
- Prisma: data access only — no business logic in queries

## Structure

```
services/<name>-service/
├── src/
│   ├── main.ts
│   ├── app.module.ts
│   ├── <domain>/
│   │   ├── <domain>.module.ts
│   │   ├── <domain>.controller.ts       ← thin: parse, validate, delegate
│   │   ├── <domain>.service.ts          ← all business logic here
│   │   ├── dto/
│   │   │   ├── create-<domain>.dto.ts   ← input validation
│   │   │   ├── update-<domain>.dto.ts
│   │   │   └── query-<domain>.dto.ts    ← pagination, filters
│   │   └── interfaces/                  ← types for this domain
│   └── common/
│       ├── guards/                      ← auth guards
│       ├── interceptors/                ← logging, transform
│       ├── filters/                     ← error handling
│       └── decorators/                  ← custom decorators
├── prisma/
│   └── schema -> symlink to packages/database/prisma/schema
├── tests/
│   ├── unit/                            ← mock Prisma, test service logic
│   └── integration/                     ← real DB, test full flow
├── package.json
├── tsconfig.json
└── Dockerfile
```

## Database — Scalable Patterns

- Prisma schema is shared: `packages/database/prisma/schema/` (multi-file by domain)
- Each service symlinks to the shared schema folder
- Always use transactions for multi-table mutations: `prisma.$transaction()`
- Use `select` to fetch only needed fields for list endpoints
- Soft delete pattern: set `deletedAt`, never hard delete clinical data
- Always filter by `organizationId` for tenant isolation
- Add `@@index` for any field used in WHERE or ORDER BY

## API Design — Scalable Patterns

### Response Format
```typescript
// Success (single)
{ data: T }

// Success (list with pagination)
{ data: T[], meta: { page, limit, total, totalPages } }

// Error
{ error: { code: string, message: string, message_key: string, trace_id: string } }
```

### Pagination (required on ALL list endpoints)
```typescript
// Query params
?page=1&limit=20&sort=createdAt&order=desc

// For large datasets, prefer cursor-based:
?cursor=<lastId>&limit=20
```

### Filtering
```typescript
// Use query DTOs with class-validator
?status=active&priority=high&search=nguyen
```

## Dependency Injection

- Use NestJS DI for all dependencies
- Services inject PrismaService, never instantiate directly
- Use interfaces for external dependencies (easier to mock in tests)
- Register providers in the module, not globally (unless truly shared)

## Testing

- Unit tests in `tests/unit/` — mock PrismaService, test business logic
- Integration tests in `tests/integration/` — use real test database
- Use `@nestjs/testing` Test.createTestingModule for proper DI
- Test edge cases: not found, duplicate, invalid input, unauthorized
- Test pagination boundaries: page 0, negative limit, very large offset
- Mock external services (RabbitMQ, MinIO, Orthanc) in unit tests

## Error Handling

```typescript
// Use specific NestJS exceptions
throw new NotFoundException({ code: 'PATIENT_NOT_FOUND', message_key: 'patient.error.notFound' });
throw new ConflictException({ code: 'DUPLICATE_MRN', message_key: 'patient.error.duplicateMrn' });
throw new ForbiddenException({ code: 'INSUFFICIENT_PERMISSION' });
```

## Event Emission (for cross-service communication)

When a significant domain event occurs, emit to RabbitMQ:
```typescript
// After creating a patient
this.eventEmitter.emit('patient.created', { patientId, organizationId, timestamp });
```
